---
import GuideLayout from '../../layouts/GuideLayout.astro';
import { computeFHA } from '../../lib/gov-loans.js';
import { computeMortgage } from '../../lib/mortgage.js';

const fmt = (n: number) => '$' + Math.round(n).toLocaleString('en-US');
// $350k, 5% down comparison
const fha = computeFHA({ price: 350000, down: 17500, annualRate: 6.25, termYears: 30 });
const conv = computeMortgage({ homePrice: 350000, downPayment: 17500, annualRate: 6.5, termYears: 30, taxRate: 0, insuranceAnnual: 0, pmiRate: 0.6, hoaMonthly: 0, extraMonthly: 0, startYear: 2026, startMonth: 8 });
const convPmiMonths = conv.rows.filter((r) => r.pmi > 0).length;
---

<GuideLayout
  title="FHA MIP vs. Conventional PMI: The Insurance Decision That Outlasts the Rate"
  metaTitle="FHA MIP vs Conventional PMI Compared | Payoff Logic"
  description="FHA charges 1.75% upfront plus annual MIP that usually never cancels; conventional PMI is credit-priced and ends automatically. A worked $350k comparison shows when each wins."
  slug="fha-mip-vs-conventional-pmi"
  updated="July 11, 2026"
  updatedISO="2026-07-11"
  kind="shield"
  tool={{ href: '/fha-loan-calculator/', label: 'FHA calculator with real MIP rules' }}
>
  <div class="answer">
    <strong>Direct answer:</strong> Conventional PMI is priced on your credit and
    cancels automatically at 78% loan-to-value. FHA charges 1.75% of the loan upfront
    <em>plus</em> annual MIP that — with under 10% down — lasts the life of the loan.
    Strong credit (roughly 680+) usually wins with conventional; weaker credit or thin
    down payments often price better with FHA, with a planned refi out of MIP later.
  </div>

  <h2>The same house, both ways ({fmt(350000)}, 5% down)</h2>
  <div class="tablewrap"><table>
    <thead><tr><th></th><th class="num">FHA @ 6.25%</th><th class="num">Conventional @ 6.5% (PMI 0.6%)</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Upfront insurance</td><td class="num">{fmt(fha.ufmip)} (financed)</td><td class="num">$0</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Monthly insurance (first month)</td><td class="num">{fmt(fha.firstMIP)}</td><td class="num">{fmt(conv.monthlyPMI)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Insurance ends</td><td class="num">never (life of loan)</td><td class="num">~{Math.round(convPmiMonths / 12)} years (78% LTV)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Total insurance if held full term</td><td class="num">{fmt(fha.totalMIP + fha.ufmip)}</td><td class="num">{fmt(conv.totalPMI)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>P&amp;I payment</td><td class="num">{fmt(fha.payment)}</td><td class="num">{fmt(conv.monthlyPI)}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table></div>
  <p>
    Notice the shape: FHA's monthly numbers look competitive early (FHA rates often
    run ~0.25% lower), but the insurance never leaves — the full-term totals aren't
    close. FHA's honest pitch is <em>access</em>: it prices insurance identically
    whether your score is 580 or 780, while conventional PMI can double for weaker
    credit or simply be unavailable.
  </p>

  <h2>Decision rules that hold up</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Score ~680+ and 5%+ down:</strong> get both quotes, but conventional usually wins — cancellable insurance is worth a slightly higher rate.</li>
    <li><strong>Score below ~660 or 3.5% down:</strong> FHA often wins today's payment. Plan the exit: build to 20% equity and refinance to conventional (run it in the <a href="/refinance-calculator/">refinance calculator</a>) — that's the standard playbook, not a loophole.</li>
    <li><strong>10%+ down on FHA:</strong> the special case where MIP does end (after 11 years) — the comparison tightens; quote both.</li>
    <li><strong>Eligible for VA:</strong> skip this whole debate — no monthly insurance at all (<a href="/va-loan-calculator/">VA calculator</a>).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The mistake to avoid</h2>
  <p>
    Choosing by rate alone. A 6.25% FHA quote can cost more than a 6.5% conventional
    once life-of-loan MIP is priced in — and the reverse can be true for weak-credit
    PMI tiers. Compare <em>rate + insurance + duration</em> in the
    <a href="/fha-loan-calculator/">FHA</a> and
    <a href="/mortgage-calculator/">conventional</a> calculators side by side, and see
    <a href="/guides/pmi-explained/">PMI explained</a> for the removal rules that make
    conventional's insurance temporary.
  </p>
</GuideLayout>
